on the Status of Cooperation with the International Criminal Court, 8 April, 2013, para 3; Side Event on Complementarity in Kenya
organized by the Wayamo Foundation during the 12th Assembly of State Parties held in The Hague in November 2013. During
both events, the AG stated that the ICD had already been established despite this not being the case.
3.“Report of the Commission of Inquiry into Post Election Violence” October 2008. The report of CIPEV is commonly referred to as

Reports/Commission_of_Inquiry_into_Post_Election_Violence.pdf
Summary
O
ne and a half years since the International Crimes Division (ICD) in the High Court of Kenya was rst proposed
by the Judicial Service Commission (JSC) in its report of October 2012
1
, there has been little concrete movement
towards actually setting up the Division. This is not in itself a criticism; such processes should take the time necessary
to achieve the desired results. However, apart from publishing the report, making several ‘bench-marking’ visits to other
countries and holding two low-key workshops, the JSC seems to have made little progress towards actualising an ICD.
Despite this inertia, the Division continues to be touted in ofcial circles as a potential answer to providing justice for
victims of post-election violence as well as a potential replacement of the ICC ongoing process. On at least two occasions,
the Attorney General has gone so far as to erroneously tell international audiences that the ICD has already been
launched.
2
While,ideally, it would make sense to await the production of the nal roadmap towards establishing the ICD,
it is important to offer a preliminary review of the process so far. This will point out potential strengths, weaknesses,
gaps and loopholes, in the hope of ensuring that the eventual outcome of the ICD establishment process is one that will
improve the chances of post-election violence victims nally getting justice.
Background
Following Kenya’s disputed presidenal elecons in 2007, violence broke out around the country.
This dark period of the country’s history, now commonly referred to as the post-elecon violence
(PEV), resulted in the death of at least 1,133 Kenyans, the displacement of over 350,000 others,
sexual violence, arson, maiming, loong and the destrucon of property worth millions of shillings.
3
The search for jusce for vicms of post-elecon violence began with the establishment of a
Commission of Inquiry on Post-elecon Violence (CIPEV), mandated to invesgate the facts and
circumstances surrounding the violence and the conduct of state security agencies in handling it
and to make recommendaons on these maers.
CIPEV recommended the creaon of a Special Tribunal for Kenya with Kenyan and internaonal
judges to sit in Kenya to try perpetrators of the violence. It set specic melines during which the
tribunal should be created and operaonalised, failing which it recommended that Ko Annan,
who chaired Kenya’s mediaon process, hand over an envelope containing a secret list of alleged
KPTJ
6
perpetrators to the Internaonal Criminal Court (ICC) Prosecutor. Despite three separate aempts,
the government failed to form the tribunal, causing the ICC to intervene.
On 31 March 2010, the ICC Pre-Trial Chamber II authorised the Prosecutor to open invesgaons
into the Kenya situaon.
4
The Prosecutor subsequently issued summons to appear against six
high prole Kenyans and, aer conrmaon hearings held in late 2011, the cases against four
of the suspects, namely Uhuru Kenyaa, William Ruto, Francis Muthaura and Joshua Sang, were
conrmed. The charges against Francis Muthaura were dropped by the Prosecutor, cing the
admission by a crical witness that he had lied in his statement. The trial of Joshua Sang and
William Ruto, the laer now Deputy President of Kenya, opened on 10 September 2013 and is
ongoing, while, aer several adjournments, that of Uhuru Kenyaa, now President of Kenya, is
scheduled to open in October 2014.
Court of last resort
While it is an important feature of the global architecture of the ght against impunity, the
Internaonal Criminal Court is a court of last resort, which exists to complement naonal
criminal jurisdicons under the principle of complementarity.
5
It therefore steps in to prosecute
internaonal crimes only when a member state is unable or unwilling to invesgate and prosecute.
6
Even then, the ICC’s prosecutorial policy mandates it to prosecute only those who allegedly bear
the greatest responsibility for the crimes. In Kenya’s case, only six individuals appeared before the
Court and the number has since been reduced to three. In a situaon of such widespread violence,
implicang hundreds-and possibly thousands - of mid-level and lower-level perpetrators, domesc
prosecuons are necessary to close the resulng gap in accountability. However, in the case of
Kenya, there have been only a handful of such prosecuons and even fewer convicons.
7
The
recent admission of the Director of Public Prosecuons that the more than 4,000 cases reviewed
by a mul-agency task force set up in June 2012 were not “prosecutable”, whether as ordinary
crimes or internaonal crimes, seemed all but to exnguish the hope of the post-elecon violence
vicms ever geng jusce in the courts through state-led prosecuons.
8

7
The Internaonal Crimes Division
of the High Court of Kenya
On 9 May 2012 the Judicial Service Commission (JSC) set up a working commiee mandated to
study and make recommendaons on the viability of establishing an Internaonal Crimes Division
(ICD) in the High Court of Kenya. Aer vising several countries to study various approaches to
domesc prosecuon of internaonal crimes, the commiee produced its rst report in October
2012.
9
The report rightly observes that the Rome Statute obligates member states to punish internaonal
crimes and that the ICC cannot deal with all post-elecon violence cases. It also notes the connuing
demand for jusce following the failure to establish a special tribunal as recommended by the
CIPEV and goes on to recommend the establishment of the ICD.
The legal framework
The legal framework proposed for the formaon of the ICD includes the Constuon, which
establishes the High Court of Kenya with unlimited original jurisdicon on civil and criminal maers;
the Internaonal Crimes Act, No. 16 of 2008 which, under Secon 8 (2), provides that the crimes
proscribed in the Act shall be tried in the High Court of Kenya; and the Judicial Service Act, Secon
5 of which gives the Chief Jusce administrave power to exercise general direcon and control
over the Judiciary and under which, presumably, the Chief Jusce would create the ICD through a
Gazee Noce. The JSC report also provides that the ICD shall apply special rules of procedure,
pracce and evidence in its operaons and conduct of trials.
Jurisdicon
Although the inial discussion of the JSC was on the possibility of operaonalising the Internaonal
Criminal Act, 2008 in order to address pending post-elecon violence cases, the report proposes
that the ICD should now have jurisdicon to prosecute not only crimes under Secon 6 of the
Internaonal Crimes Act - that is, genocide, war crimes and crimes against humanity - but also
transnaonal crimes including drug tracking, human tracking, money laundering, cybercrime,
terrorism and piracy, and any other internaonal crimes as may be proscribed under any
internaonal instrument that Kenya is a party to.
9. Judicial Services Commission, "Report of the Committee of the Judicial Service Commission on the establishment of an
International Crimes Division in the High Court of Kenya" (JSC Report), 30 October 2012.
KPTJ
8
Proposed structure
The report proposes that the ICD should be modelled on the standards of the ICC at The Hague,
with the same rules, pracces and procedures being adopted.
10
Seven judges would be appointed
to sit in the ICD in panels of three, with one extra judge in case one of the judges cannot sit.
Once the judges for this Division have been idened, they would undergo rigorous training in
internaonal criminal law and related subjects, through long-term and short-term courses. The
seat of the proposed Division will be in Nairobi but it can also operate by circuit and may sit and
conduct proceedings in any other place in Kenya as the Chief Jusce may direct.
Prosecuon
The JSC report recommends that there should be established a well-equipped independent
prosecuon unit within the oce of the Director of Public Prosecuons to deal exclusively with
internaonal crimes. At the same me, it also says that Parliament should enact legislaon to
provide for the appointment of a Special Prosecutor who shall be responsible for the prosecuon
of cases that fall within the jurisdicon of the ICD under Arcle 157(12) of the Constuon of
Kenya. These two recommendaons are confusing as they are contradictory. If an independent
prosecuon unit were to be established within the DPP’s oce, then it would not be necessary or
feasible to appoint a special prosecutor under Arcle 157(12). The DPP, who has publicly stated
that he regards post-elecon violence cases as unprosecutable, has made clear his reservaons
to what would amount to taking away some of his powers and vesng them in an independent
prosecutor. On the other hand, the appointment of a Special Prosecutor under Arcle 157(12)
would require new legislaon by Parliament and it is highly doubul that the necessary polical
will would be forthcoming.
11
Challenges, Gaps And Weaknesses
Jurisdicon
As already stated, the proposed ICD is to have jurisdicon to prosecute two categories of crime,
namely core internaonal crimes such as genocide, war crimes and crimes against humanity,
and transnaonal and organised crimes, which are domesc crimes with potenal cross-border
elements, such as terrorism, piracy, drug tracking, cybercrime etc. While the JSC report
acknowledges the hitherto limited prosecuons of mid-level and low-level perpetrators of post-
elecon violence as a key driver behind the formaon of the proposed ICD, it does not give a
sound policy juscaon for lumping together both categories of crime. This is intriguing given the
10. It is not clear how the ICD can adopt the rules, practices and procedures of the ICC since the latter’s rules are an
amalgam of both common law and civil law traditions while Kenya is a purely common law country.
11. See below on anti-accountability environment.
KPTJ
9
fact that the criminal jusce system has had no problems prosecung transnaonal crimes with
some success, even in the absence of a specialised division of the High Court. Further, many of
the transnaonal crimes named are currently prosecutable in the rst instance in the magistrates’
courts with possible appeals lying in the High Court, the Court of Appeal and, in appropriate
instances, the Supreme Court. Removing these crimes from the ambit of magistrates’ courts and
giving the jurisdicon to prosecute them to a division of the High Court would require a change
in legislaon and cannot simply be done by the Chief Jusce through a gazee noce, as the JSC
report seems to envisage.
Giving the proposed ICD the mandate to prosecute both categories of crimes also runs the risk of
the court being kept busy with prosecuons of drug trackers and terror suspects, while never
seriously addressing the more polically sensive cases of post-elecon violence. This would give
the illusion of movement in the search of jusce for post-elecon violence crimes while in reality
the situaon would remain unchanged.
Absence of polical will
The limited number of domesc prosecuons of post-elecon violence crimes is aributable either
to a lack of proper invesgaons or to a lacklustre approach to their prosecuon by the Oce of
the Director of Public Prosecuons, which appears content to tell the public that the cases are
unprosecutable, without stang how the Director of Public Prosecuons has used his considerable
powers under the Constuon to improve their fortunes in court. This lack of polical will, which
has stood in the way of jusce for vicms of post-elecon violence for the last six years, cannot
be xed merely by seng up an internaonal crimes division. This is because, under Kenya’s legal
system, judges do not invesgate or prosecute cases; they adjudicate over them as neutral arbiters.
This means that, without meaningful reforms in the invesgave and prosecutorial arms of the
criminal jusce system, the proposed ICD could end up being a white elephant, with no cases to
prosecute.
Hosle, an-accountability environment
Of equal concern is the fact that the debate on the proposed ICD has been taking place in an
ocial environment that is decidedly opposed to accountability. Since the elecon in March 2013
of Uhuru Kenyaa and William Ruto as President and Deputy President respecvely, and despite
surveys consistently showing public support for accountability, the government of Kenya has gone
to great lengths to stop the cases facing the two at the ICC. The fallout from the legal, polical
and diplomac oensive conducted to this end has negavely aected the prospects of obtaining
jusce for vicms of post-elecon violence at home. The most notable example of this is the
KPTJ
10
moon that was passed in the Naonal Assembly and the Senate in September 2013 to withdraw
Kenya from the Rome Statute and to repeal the Internaonal Crimes Act.
12
Although the moon
has not yet been acted upon by the Execuve and Kenya remains a member of the ICC for now, it
is unclear how the ICD would funcon in the absence of the Internaonal Crimes Act, which the
JSC report designates as a key pillar of the ICD’s legal framework.
Inadequate witness protecon
The JSC report acknowledges the importance of an eecve witness protecon agency to the
successful prosecuon of internaonal and transnaonal crimes. It recommends that “the
government should fully fund and make operaonal the exisng Witness Protecon Agency”
(WPA).
13
In so doing, the JSC recognises the inadequacy of the WPA in its current state. This is a
serious shortcoming that has the potenal to sabotage any eorts aimed at domesc accountability
for serious crimes. The WPA is seriously underfunded: in nancial year 2013/2014, it received
only Ksh 196 million (2.2 million US dollars) of the Ksh 500 million (six million US dollars) that it
requested.
According to experts, witness protecon in Kenya seems to lack the polical support necessary
to make it eecve because it is viewed in the light of the ICC and the eorts to hold high prole
policians accountable.
14
The WPA also has an image problem that makes it dicult for potenal
witnesses to entrust it with their safety, especially when they are called upon to tesfy against
powerful polical interests. While it is formally independent, the fact that the WPA began its life as
a department in the Oce of the Aorney General and that its board includes senior government
ocials, among them the Aorney General, the Inspector General of Police and the Head of the
Naonal Intelligence Service, may make potenal witnesses doubt its independence from the
execuve arm of the government.
Retroacve prosecuon of internaonal crimes
The JSC report recognises a potenal obstacle to prosecung post-elecon violence crimes as
internaonal crimes under the Internaonal Crimes Act. This is because the Act came into force in
January 2009, prior to which core internaonal crimes of genocide, war crimes and crimes against
humanity did not exist as such in the laws of Kenya. It is a general principle of both internaonal law
and the Kenyan Constuon that a person cannot be punished for an act that did not constute
12. Kenya parliament votes to withdraw from ICC, Al Jazeera Africa, http://www.aljazeera.com/news/
africa/2013/09/201395151027359326.html
13. JSC Report, page 149
14. Wanja Gathu, Institute of War and Peace Reporting, “Big Questions About Witness Protection in Kenya.” 27 May 2014 - http://
iwpr.net/report-news/big-questions-about-witness-protection-kenya
KPTJ
11
an oence at the me it was commied. This is known as the principle of non-retroacvity of
the law. This refers to the requirement that the law should not extend its scope to maers that
occurred before the law was enacted. This legal principle is best encapsulated in the Lan maxim
as “nullum crimen, nulla poena sine lege scripta,” meaning nothing is a crime and no punishment
may be imposed except by a wrien law or “nullum crimen, nulla poena sine lege praevia,” which
translates as ‘nothing is a crime except as provided by law and no punishment may be imposed
except as previuosly provided by law’; that is to say, the law must pre-exist the crime.
Kenya raed the Rome Statute in 2005 and domescated it through the Internaonal Crimes Act
in 2008, aer the post-elecon violence. The Act became operaonal on 1 January 2009. The Act
provides for prosecuon of crimes against humanity domescally in Kenya but cannot be applied
to crimes that were perpetrated between 2007-2008 before the Act was passed into law.
In its report, the JSC has argued that there should be no reason under internaonal law that the
Internaonal Crimes Act, or any other subsequent Act, cannot be used to prosecute crimes that
predate its enactment. This is because the principle of non-retroacvity would not be violated
where the conduct to be prosecuted was already a crime under internaonal law.
Unsound legal interpretaon?
The report suggests that since the Constuon of Kenya 2010 acknowledges that all convenons
raed by the State are part of Kenyan law, then the Rome Statute was a part of Kenyan law from
2005, when Kenya raed it. As such, the report argues, perpetrators of internaonal crimes in
2007-2008 were therefore comming pre-exisng crimes and can be prosecuted under the Rome
Statute as read with the Penal Code and should not be limited by the Internaonal Crimes Act.
However, not only is this an expedient interpretaon of the law, it is not legally sound. This is
because treaes are specic as to me, content and jurisdicon. They come into force only upon
racaon and, where a State's legal system is dualist, a further step of domescaon is required.
A dualist state, as opposed to a monist one, is a state whose laws require that all treaes, in addion
to being signed and raed by the state, must be adopted through naonal legislaon before their
provisions can become part of the domesc law. At the me of racaon of the Rome Statute,
Kenya was a dualist state and therefore domescaon was necessary. Kenya domescated the
Rome Statute in 2008 aer the post-elecon violence and therefore the treaty only has eect
aer this domescaon. It would be important to clearly establish why this case should be an
excepon, which the JSC report does not do convincingly.
Secondly, an observaon of analogous situaons indicates that retroacvity cannot be provided
for in a carte blanche provision that allows a look into all past atrocies of a naon. Whilst following
KPTJ
12
the JSC’s recommendaon would mean the possible prosecuon of all alleged internaonal crimes
commied aer 2005, best pracce in Timor l’Este, Rwanda and the Democrac Republic of Congo
shows that a retroacve clause in legislaon should be limited to a specic me to deal with a
specic atrocity and not be open to all past historical injusces. There has to be a limited scope
in which the retroacvity provision operates, in order to prevent states from assuming unlimited
power and potenally abusing this provision. Therefore, while it is important and necessary to
prosecute serious post-elecon crimes as internaonal crimes, more thought needs to be given to
how to get around the retroacvity obstacle than the JSC has included in its report. This will avoid
the danger of the prosecuons being challenged for unconstuonality once they get underway.
Lack of stakeholder input
The process of debang the possible establishment of the ICD has been faulted for lacking adequate
consultaon with key stakeholders, especially relevant civil society actors and vicm groups. Long
before the JSC recommended the formaon of the ICD, civil society had been grappling with the
challenge of closing the gap in prosecuons and had held various consultaons and produced
a number of reports on the issue.
15
However, when the JSC process got under way, there was
no aempt to bring civil society on board at the outset. What passed for consultaon was a
breakfast meeng at which the JSC shared its proposals with lile room for feedback. Subsequent
communicaons between the JSC and civil society on the issue have been intermient and
procedural, without a plaorm for proper engagement in which the JSC might respond to civil
society’s concerns and incorporate its input into the process.
Posive complementarity
The purpose of establishing a domesc mechanism to prosecute crimes against humanity through
an ICD or other mechanism is to complement exisng prosecuon at the Internaonal Criminal
Court (ICC) and not to replace the ICC process, as some local proponents of the ICD have suggested.
The prosecuons at the ICD also have to be a legimate eort to pursue jusce for vicms of
post-elecon violence in accordance with internaonal standards and not designed to shield
perpetrators of crimes against humanity from jusce.
In addion, ICD proceedings should be designed to plug the gap in the prosecuon of mid to lower
level perpetrators, and not merely to iniate token prosecuon of lower-level perpetrators so as
to disguise the lack of prosecuon of elite perpetrators. This means that the ICD must also pursue
higher-level suspects. Only then can the ICD be viewed to be legimate. Legimacy would also be
15. e.g. Kenyans for Peace with Truth and Justice, “The Post-Election Violence in Kenya: Seeking Justice for Victims.” http://www.
africog.org/reports/KPTJ%20SPECIAL%20REPORT_Seeking%20Justice%20for%20PEV%20Victims.pdf
KPTJ
13
conferred on the ICD if it had judges and prosecutors drawn from among local and internaonal
legal praconers, judges and scholars. This would give it access to internaonal best pracce and
experse, as well as address any suspicion of potenal bias that tends to accompany domesc
instuons that seek to pursue jusce in a polically polarised environment such as that in Kenya.
Recommendaons
• The JSC sub-commiee on the establishment of the ICD should embark on proper consultaons
with key actors including relevant civil society organisaons, vicm groups and academics, to
develop proper consensus on how to establish an adequate complementarity mechanism for
Kenya.
• The JSC report’s proposal to retroacvely prosecute post-elecon crimes as internaonal crimes
needs to be beer thought out and supported, if the Internaonal Crimes Act is to remain the
legal basis to prosecute crimes from 2007/8. Part of the JSC’s arguments must emphasise the
grave nature of internaonal crimes and that the obligaon to prosecute is incumbent on all
states under internaonal law. An acknowledgement by the Internaonal Law Commission and
the Internaonal Court of Jusce that crimes against humanity are violaons of jus cogens (that
is, certain fundamental, overriding principles of internaonal law, from which no derogaon is
ever permied) means that the responsibility to prosecute these violaons cannot be limited by
naonal statute even as concerns retroacvity.
• Despite the diculty in obtaining the necessary polical will, the legislave framework
establishing the ICD should be a parliamentary statute as opposed to an administrave decision
by the Chief Jusce, as appears to be currently envisaged. This will insulate the process of
invesgaon and prosecuon from subsequent polical interference whilst providing a legal
basis both for funding as well as administrave funcons such as issuance of summons. A statute
would also provide a legal framework for engagement with experts in internaonal criminal
jusce, allowing for the possible secondment of internaonal actors, such as prosecutors and
possibly judicial ocers. The statute would also regulate the qualicaons of persons to be
appointed as prosecutors.
• There is a need to harmonise all relevant legislaon, parcularly the Evidence Act, to respond to
evidenary standards for crimes commied in an environment of conict or generalised violence;
the Criminal Procedure Code, in light of the unique requirements of prosecung internaonal
crimes and the Penal Code to provide a basis for sentencing alongside the Internaonal Crimes
Act, should it be amended to apply retroacvely.

14
• With regard to the jurisdicon of the ICD, whereas the inclusion of transnaonal and organised
crimes widens the ambit of the ICD by giving it a role beyond internaonal crimes, the High
Court of Kenya as presently constuted, as well as the Penal Code, Criminal Procedure Code,
internaonal convenons raed by Kenya which form part of Kenyan law through Arcle 2 (5)
and 2 (6) of the Constuon of Kenya and relevant statutes, are able to address these violaons
and have already done so in the past fairly successfully.
16
It is therefore necessary for the JSC to
clearly jusfy the proposed mixed jurisdicon of the ICD. A beer alternave, given the urgency
of addressing post-elecon violence, would be to sequence the work of the ICD so that it deals
with post-elecon violence cases on a priority basis, aer which its jurisdicon may be expanded
to include transnaonal crimes.
Conclusion
The recommendaon to establish an Internaonal Crimes Division of the High Court of Kenya
is welcome in principle, as part of the enduring search for jusce for vicms of post-elecon
violence. However the Judicial Service Commission report recommending the establishment of
the ICD raises as many quesons as it aempts to answer. Much more thought needs to be put
into addressing concerns regarding the proposed legal framework, the mixed jurisdicon of the
ICD, the invesgaon and prosecuon of the crimes, witness protecon and the harmonisaon of
exisng legislaon necessary to ensure that the resulng mechanism becomes a real opon for
delivering jusce for vicms of post-elecon violence. Key actors and stakeholders in the search for
jusce, especially vicm groups and relevant civil society organisaons that have worked on and
thought about these issues consistently, and for a sustained period of me, should be genuinely
engaged and their input sought for every stage of the process. These measures are necessary to
ensure that once established, the proposed Internaonal Crimes Division becomes a viable opon
for jusce for vicms of post-elecon violence and not just an expensive white elephant.
